<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>is a relatively long-lived plant. Comanor and Clark (2000) found that <i>Y. brevifolia </i>is a relatively fast-growing plant. Juvenile plants are generally not branched and open; middle-aged plants are forked and dense, and older trees have a single stem with an open crown. Seedlings are uncommon except following a series of wet years. Some researchers believe that sexual reproduction was more common during wetter climatic periods in the past (Webb et al. 2003), while vegetative reproduction is now the most important mode of regeneration on many sites (Gucker 2006c). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Yucca brevifolia </i>is a conspicuous and picturesque signature for the Mojave Desert. Its range defines the region in general, but the plant is not evenly distributed. Different ecotypes occupy specific subregions, and each has somewhat different environmental requirements. Munz (1959) recognized a long-leaved, tall form from the central, northern, and southern Mojave (var. <i>brevifolia</i>), a short-leaved, clonal, multi-stemmed form (var. <i>herbertii</i>) from the western Mojave, and a short-leaved, tall form (var<i>. jaegeriana</i>) from the eastern Mojave. Some populations are better adapted than others to sprouting from adventitious roots and stems following damage by fire or other mechanical disturbance. However, a great deal of plasticity exists in the species. Recent taxonomic treatments (Hess and Robbins 2002, Hickman 1993) did not recognize these varieties. <br/>
<br/>
Despite the comments by Rowlands (1978), we find merit in recognizing a <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>alliance based on recent work (Thomas et al. 2004). However, there is a high degree of stand-to-stand variation in structure and species composition (Keeler-Wolf and Thomas 2000, Thomas et al. 2004). Joshua trees can grow over open canopy of shrubs or grasses. These physiognomic types suggest two different fire and grazing disturbance regimes; see Hogan (1977) and Vasek and Barbour (1977). Presence of disturbance-related shrubs such as <i>Cylindropuntia acanthocarpa, Sphaeralcea ambigua, </i>and <i>Gutierrezia microcephala </i>suggest high grazing intensity. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
