<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Summer lighting strikes are relatively frequent in the high desert, where large individuals make suitable targets. The fire resistance of trees increases with age because the thick mat of dried leaves along the trunk decreases with age, and the corky bark of older trunks serves as a firebreak (Gucker 2006c). Plants respond to fire by sprouting after low-severity fires, but high-severity fires may kill them. 

Fire regimes vary in frequency and severity throughout range of the alliance, which can be reflected by the species associated with <i>Yucca brevifolia</i>. Many stands have important <i>Pleuraphis jamesii </i>understories (Keeler-Wolf and Thomas 2000). This and other desert perennial grasses (except <i>Muhlenbergia porteri</i>) spread at the expense of shrubs at relatively high fire return intervals, although the grasses may decrease following spring burns in low-rainfall years (Simonin 2000c). In contrast, the presence of <i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>and other long-lived shrubs suggests long disturbance-free intervals for other stands.</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
