    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ac-d, Af-l, An-p). Most stands in the western sections occur on bajadas at the bases of the Liebre, San Gabriel, Scodie, and Tehachapi mountains, which have the clonal <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> var. <i>herbertii.</i> Agriculture and development have destroyed most of these stands. The remaining have <i>Achnatherum speciosum, A. hymenoides, Larrea tridentata,</i> and <i>Poa secunda,</i> or if degraded, <i>Ambrosia salsola, Ericameria linearifolia,</i> and <i>E. nauseosa.</i> Stands in eastern subsections are well described, and they occur between the low-elevation creosote bush zone and the higher pinyon-juniper zone (Keeler-Wolf and Thomas 2000, Thomas et al. 2004). They have <i>Pleuraphis jamesii</i> as the principal grass at higher elevations and<i> P. rigida</i> below 1400 m, including those in Joshua Tree National Park.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stands occur around Walker Pass and westward into the Scodie Mountains and the upper Canebrake Creek Valley, east of Lake Isabella.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands occur in the Coso, Cottonwood, and Inyo mountains, where they mix with those of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Atriplex confertifolia, Coleogyne ramosissima,</i> and <i>Juniperus osteosperma</i> alliances (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bb, Bd, Bg, Bi). Stands occur on the desert slopes of the Liebre, San Gabriel, San Bernardino, and Little San Bernardino mountains.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Livestock has heavily impacted many <i>Yucca brevifolia </i>woodlands. Grazing does not improve range conditions of their dry, harsh environment, and efforts to improve the range are expensive and yield few benefits (Gucker 2006c). Extensive vandalism has occurred in many areas. 

Increased fire frequency, resulting from concomitant effects of human ignition and fine fuel buildup, is likely to degrade stands in some parts of the allianceâ€™s range. We should study historic fire regimes throughout the range of the alliance to establish appropriate recommendations </div>
</div>

    

    

